    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-03-18T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-03-18T15:00:00-05:00" n="769"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d769">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/4086½: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-03-18T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 18, 1919, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7765. Repeat to Mission and to London. Vice Consul <persName>Imbrie</persName> at
                    Viborg telegraphs March 14<note n="10" xml:id="d769fn10">Not printed.</note>
                    that General <persName>Tesloff</persName>, commander of the Finnish forces on
                    the Russian frontier and personally representing <persName corresp="#p_MGCGEB1"
                        >General Mannerheim</persName>, assures him that he and <persName
                        corresp="#p_MGCGEB1">General Mannerheim</persName> are both of the opinion
                    that it will be necessary to take Petrograd in order to save Finland from the
                    Bolsheviki. General <persName>Tesloff</persName> believes the problem is not
                    serious from a military standpoint but says the continued occupation of the city
                    will depend wholly on obtaining food supplies. General
                        <persName>Tesloff</persName> also informed Vice Consul
                        <persName>Imbrie</persName> that Finland would expect the Murman Peninsula
                    as a reward for taking Petrograd. Vice Consul <persName>Imbrie</persName> states
                    that in his relations with General <persName>Tesloff</persName> he will exercise
                    extreme caution not to arouse false hopes or in any way to commit this
                    Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PFL">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
